            NAME
            make.arrow - Draws an arrow symbol to show approximate north
            orientation on the map composition.
            
            SYNOPSIS
            make.arrow [filename]            make.arrow           
            
            DESCRIPTION
            make.arrow produces a graphic symbol to show north
            orientation on the map composition.  The user must respond
            to a series of questions regarding the pen selection, the
            height of the "N" in the north arrow, and location of the
            arrow symbol.  If given, the [filename] is used as the name
            of the overlay created.
            
            The user is required to provide the following:
            
                 - map definition file name
                 - overlay file name (if not specified on the command
                      line)
                 - plotter pen number
                 - relationship of the arrow to a window within the
                      map composition
                 - arrow symbol length (which is approximately 2.5 times
                      the height of the "N")
                 - location for the middle of the "N" in the the symbol
            
            Completing the response sequence generates the required
            files to construct the map element.  Definition parameters
            are stored in the misc directory; graphic elements to draw
            the map on the screen or plotter are stored in the ovm
            directory.  The default file name for both directories is
            northarrow.
            
            Changing the appearance of the north arrow (e.g. location,
            size, etc.) can be done by regenerating the make.arrow
            command and overwriting the initial file, or by editing the
            parameter file, then executing the redo command.
            
                 (edit) example:          vi misc/[filename]
                                          vi misc/n.arrow
            
            Information entered through the interactive make.arrow
            command has been reformatted to meet the requirements of the
            MAPGEN command legend, prefacing the element characteristics
            with options for the legend command.  All options available
            in the legend command are available for use in the GRASS-
            MAPGEN Interface.  Commonly used legend options associated

